[[File:高松塚古墳.jpg|thumb|Takamatsuzuka Tomb]] The {{nihongo|'''Takamatsuzuka Tomb'''|高松塚古墳|''Takamatsuzuka Kofun''}} is an ancient {{ill|Round Kofun|lt=circular tomb|ja|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Round Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Round Kofun|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} in [[:en:Asuka, Nara|Asuka village]], [[:en:Nara Prefecture|Nara Prefecture]], [[:en:Japan|Japan]].
==History== The tomb is thought to have been built at some time between the end of the 7th century and the beginning of the 8th century. It was accidentally discovered by a local farmer in the 1960s. ==Description== [[File:Takamat1.jpg|thumb|A mural of women on the western wall of the tomb]] The mound of the tomb was built of alternating layers of [[:en:Clay|Clay]] and [[sand]]. It is about {{convert |16|m}} in diameter and {{convert|5|m}} high. Excavation yielded a burial chamber with painted [[:en:fresco|fresco]] wall paintings of [[:en:Courtier|Courtier]]s in [[:en:Goguryeo|Goguryeo]]-style garb. The paintings are in full color with red, blue, gold, and silver foil representing four male followers and four serving maidens together with the [[:en:Azure Dragon (Chinese constellation) |Azure Dragon]], [[:en:Black Tortoise (Chinese constellation)|Black Tortoise]], [[White Tiger (Chinese constellation)|White Tiger]], and [[Vermilion Bird (Chinese constellation)|Vermilion Bird]] groups of stars. The paintings are [[:en:Cultural Property (Japan)|designated]] a [[National Treasures of Japan|National Treasure]].
For whom the tomb was built is unknown, but the decorations suggest it is for a member of the Japanese royal family or a high-Ranking nobleman. Candidates include:
# [[Prince Osakabe]] (d. 705), a son of [[:en:Emperor Tenmu|Emperor Tenmu]] # [[Prince Yuge]] (d. 699), also a son of Emperor Tenmu # [[Prince Takechi]] ({{circa|654}} – 696), also a son of Emperor Temmu, general of [[:en:Jinshin War|Jinshin War]], [[:en:Daijō Daijin|Daijō Daijin]] # Isonokami Ason Maro (640–717), a descendant of [[Mononobe clan]] and in charge of [[:en:Fujiwara-kyō|Fujiwara-kyō]] after the capital was moved to [[Heijō-kyō]] # [[:en:Kudara no Konikishi|Kudara no Konikishi Zenkō]] (617–700), a son of the last king of [[:en:Baekje|Baekje]], one of the [[Three Kingdoms of Korea]].<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.asukanet.gr.jp/asukahome/ASUKA2/TAKAMATUTUKA/takamatutuka.html | work = Asuka | title = Takamatuzuka | publisher = Asuka net | place = [[:en:Japan | JP]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nara-np.co.jp/special/takamatu/vol_02d_01.html |title=特集 高松塚光源 |website= Nara-np | place = JP |access-date= 13 January 2022 | language = ja |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070907112805/http://www.nara-np.co.jp/special/takamatu/vol_02d_01.html |archive-date=7 September 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref>
==Conservation== The [[:en:Cultural Affairs Agency|Cultural Affairs Agency]] of Japan is{{As of? |date=February 2024}} considering taking apart the stone chamber and reassembling it elsewhere to prevent further deterioration to its wall paintings. A painting called ''Asuka Bijin'', or "beautiful women", is one of the [[mural]]s in the tomb facing deterioration. The unusual preservation method is being considered because the tomb's current situation makes it impossible to prevent further damage and stop the spread of [[Mold (fungus)|mold]].
Unlike the [[Kitora Tomb]], in Asuka removing pieces of the Takamatsuzuka wall [[:en:Plaster|Plaster]] and reinforcing them for conservation appears difficult because the plaster has numerous tiny cracks.{{Citation needed|date=June 2022}}
==Comparison== In 2012, similar mural was found in a tomb in [[Mongolia]]. The round mound, thought to be built by [[:en:Göktürks|Göktürks]] in the 7th century, was excavated by Mongolian and Kazakh researchers. The mural depicts Azure Dragon and White Tiger with a procession of Chinese and [[Sogdians|Sogdian]], and other Caucasoid traders.
== Gallery == <gallery> File:Takamatsuzuka Asuka Bijin.jpg|A detail of the ''Asuka Bijin'' mural in the tomb File:高松塚古墳壁画 (複製).JPG|A reproduction of the murals at [[:en:Kansai University|Kansai University]] Museum File:Asuka Byako.JPEG|A painting of a [[White Tiger (mythology)|''byakko'']] in the tomb </gallery>
==See also== *[[:en:Detachment of wall paintings|Detachment of wall paintings]] *[[:en:en:List of National Treasures of Japan (paintings)|en:List of National Treasures of Japan (paintings)]] *[[List of Special Places of Scenic Beauty, Special Historic Sites and Special Natural Monuments]] *[[:en:Asuka-Fujiwara|Asuka-Fujiwara]]
